<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1901-07-03T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1901-07-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="513" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d513">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hill</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Russell</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1901-07-03"><hi rend="italic">July 3,
                                1901.</hi></date></dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 426.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to your No. 629, of the 15th,
                            and the Department’s telegram of the 22d ultimo, I have to say that the
                            Department is in receipt of a letter from the Acting Secretary of the
                            Navy stating that his Department is unable to understand how the <hi rend="italic">Mayflower</hi> violated treaty stipulations with
                            Venezuela by visiting Porlamar, inasmuch as that port is declared by the
                            Hacienda code to be open for export and for the importation of certain
                            articles.</p>
                        <p>You may take this statement to the Government of Venezuela.</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">David J. Hill</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Acting Secretary.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>